Amoxapine exhibits Dopamine-D2 blocking properties associated with antipsychotics but remains classified strictly as a tricyclic antidepressant based on indications and official categorizations; thus, it is not considered an atypical antipsychotic. \boxed{B}

The correct response is B because although amoxapine affects dopamine receptors like typical antipsychotics, it lacks both the intended psychiatric indication for psychosis management and formal inclusion under the category of antipsychotics according to medical classifications. \boxed{B}

